{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517861"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12842"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12842"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.44,0.05,0.31,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5285"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113034"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5285"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95066"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1049"},{"type":"tags","id":"3732"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9327"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36791"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45982"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113034"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, and severe muscle cramps. Two days ago, he started treatment with cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, prednisone and rituximab for a recently diagnosed stage IV diffuse large B-cell lymphoma with extensive disease. His regular medications include allopurinol, valaciclovir, trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, and fluconazole.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 144/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. He has dry mucous membranes. His electrocardiogram demonstrates sinus tachycardia without conduction abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 5.6 mmol/L (3.6-5.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhosphate 2.4 mmol/L (1.0-1.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 140 mmol/L (136-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUric acid 780 \u00b5mol/L (208-428)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium 1.6 mmol/L (2.0-2.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR 45 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (90-120)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 120 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 26 mmol/L (22-32)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase allopurinol dose","Calcium gluconate","Sodium bicarbonate","Rasburicase","Sevelamer"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETumour lysis syndrome (TLS) arises when rapid tumour cell breakdown releases potassium, phosphate and nucleic acids, leading to hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, secondary hypocalcaemia, and hyperuricaemia. High-grade lymphomas and acute leukaemias are at particular risk, especially after cytotoxic therapy. Early recognition and intervention aim to prevent acute kidney injury and arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has recent initiation of multi-agent chemotherapy for diffuse large Bcell lymphoma and now has hyperuricaemia, hyperphosphataemia, mild hyperkalaemia, hypocalcaemia and early renal impairment. The most important immediate action is aggressive intravenous hydration and rapid uric acid reduction with \u003Cstrong\u003Erasburicase\u003C/strong\u003E, which enzymatically converts uric acid to allantoin, a highly soluble metabolite that is readily excreted, thereby reducing the risk of uric acid nephropathy and supporting renal recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllopurinol\u003C/strong\u003E would further inhibit xanthine oxidase to prevent new uric acid formation, but it does not lower the markedly elevated existing uric acid quickly; it is suited to prophylaxis rather than urgent treatment in established TLS. There is no role for increasing the dose for the management of established TLS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHyperkalaemia is common in TLS. If there is an associated hyperkalaemic emergency (for example, arrhythmia or electrocardiogram instability), \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium gluconate\u003C/strong\u003E would be required to stabilise the myocardium. In this vignette there are no conduction abnormalities and the potassium elevation is mild, so this is not the priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E to alkalinise urine is not recommended because it can promote calciumphosphate precipitation within renal tubules and there is no metabolic acidosis here (bicarbonate is within reference values).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevelamer\u003C/strong\u003E is a phosphate binder that may help persistent hyperphosphataemia, but it does not address the urgent need for rapid uric acid reduction and renal protection; hydration and rasburicase take precedence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tumour lysis syndrome (TLS) requires prompt aggressive intravenous hydration and rapid uric acid reduction to protect renal function.","Rasburicase rapidly lowers uric acid in TLS, whereas allopurinol prevents formation and is not suitable for urgent reduction."],"references":["Howard SC, Avagyan A, Workeneh B, Pui CH. Tumour lysis syndrome [published correction appears in Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2024 Sep 9;10(1):65. doi: 10.1038/s41572-024-00557-3]. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2024;10(1):58. Published 2024 Aug 22. doi:10.1038/s41572-024-00542-w","Howard, Scott C., Deborah P. Jones, and Ching-Hon Pui. \u0022The tumor lysis syndrome.\u0022 New England Journal of Medicine 364.19 (2011): 1844-1854. Available from: https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMra0904569","Durani U, Hogan WJ. Emergencies in haematology: tumour lysis syndrome. Br J Haematol. 2020;188(4):494-500. doi:10.1111/bjh.16278"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95066"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12842"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95066"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-09T11:28:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-09T11:29:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5285"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113034"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{